<section>
    <h2>Description</h2>
    <p>The <code>&lt;li&gt;</code> element represents a single item in a list. It must be a direct child of an <a href="/docs/elements/native/ul/"><code>&lt;ul&gt;</code></a> (unordered list), <a href="/docs/elements/native/ol/"><code>&lt;ol&gt;</code></a> (ordered list), or <a href="/docs/elements/native/menu/"><code>&lt;menu&gt;</code></a> element.</p>
    <p>List items can contain any flow content, including text, links, images, and nested lists.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>When to Use</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>As a direct child of <code>&lt;ul&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;ol&gt;</code>, or <code>&lt;menu&gt;</code></li>
      <li>To wrap individual items in any list structure</li>
      <li>For navigation menu items (inside <code>&lt;nav&gt;</code> with <code>&lt;ul&gt;</code>)</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>When Not to Use</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Outside of a list container &mdash; it is invalid HTML</li>
      <li>For definition list content &mdash; use <a href="/docs/elements/native/dt/"><code>&lt;dt&gt;</code></a> and <a href="/docs/elements/native/dd/"><code>&lt;dd&gt;</code></a></li>
    </ul>
  </section>

